## Elbow Method 
## ( Create an Elbow plot when th no.of clusters to consider isn't given)
## cdist heps in finding out different kind of distance measures including the enclidean distance
## Run a loop for 20 odd iterations 
## cdist find how far away each row of the data is from all the clusters
## np.min - Find the mibimum distance 
## Sum - Sum the Minimum distance 
## Wss.append - Appended to the WSS to obtain Within Sum of Sqaures 
from scipy.spatial.distance import cdist
K=range(1,20)
wss = []
for k in K :
    kmeans = cluster.KMeans(n_clusters=k,init="k-means++")
    kmeans.fit(dat_scaled)
    wss.append(sum(np.min(cdist(dat_scaled,kmeans.cluster_centers_, 'euclidean'),
                          axis=1)) / dat_scaled.shape[0])
In [61]:
## plt.plot - plot the WSS corresponding to each value of K
plt.plot(K,wss,'bx')
plt.xlabel('k')
plt.ylabel('WSS')
plt.title('Selecting k with the Elbow Method')
plt.show()

## Silhouette measure- Another measure of goodness of cluster fit
## In scikit learn the silhouette score method has a parameter to specify the no of observations to be randomly chosen for 
# computing the silhouette score
## The silhouette score is 0.28 for the cluster model with 58 clusters 
## silhouette s ore near 1 = optimal cluster assignments
## silhouette s ore near 0 = not optimal cluster assignments
metrics.silhouette_score(dat_scaled,labels,metric="euclidean",sample_size=10000,random_state=200)

def get_images(path):
    im=cv2.imred(path)
    im=cv2.cvtColor(im,cv2.COLOR_BGR2GREY)
    im=cv2.resize(im,(90,135),cv2.INTER_LINEAR)
    i=im[0:100,:]
    return i

    clf=BaggingClassifier(oob_score=True,n_jobs=-1,n_estimators=w,random_state=400,
                         base_estimator=DecisionTreeClassifier())
    clf.fit(X_train,y_train)
    oob=clf.oob_score_
    print 'For n_estimators = '+str(w)
    print 'OOB score is '+str(oob)
    print '************************'
